Adolphus Edward Shelley ( 1812 - -1854 ) was an early British colonial official and the first Auditor - General in British Hong Kong .
Roy Royston ( 5 April 1899 -- 7 October 1976 ) , whose original name was Roy Charles Crowden , was an English actor who appeared in a large number of films between 1912 and 1966 , beginning as a child actor .
Sir Thomas Ormsby , 3rd Baronet ( 26 May 1795 in Clogan , Mayo , Ireland -- 9 August 1833 in Cowes , Isle of Wight ) succeeded as 3rd Baronet Ormsby in November 1821 .
Muircheartach Óg Ó Súilleabháin ( c. 1710 - 1754 ) , soldier , smuggler .
Marion Herbert Hoover ( known as M. Herbert Hoover or Herbert Hoover ) ( Born Asheville , Ohio ; died 1952 ) of Akron , Ohio , was an American politician of the Republican party who ran unsuccessfully for a number of elective offices in Ohio .
George W. Dollar ( 1917 - -2006 ) was a prominent preacher , teacher and author in Independent Fundamental Baptist circles .
Ronald Humpston ( 14 December 1924 - 4 January 2012 ) was a former professional footballer , who played for Portsmouth , Huddersfield Town & Headington United .
Francis `` Frank '' Joseph Hardy , ( 21 March 1917 -- 28 January 1994 ) publishing as Frank Hardy was an Australian left - wing novelist and writer best known for his controversial novel Power Without Glory .
Rabbi Avraham Grodzinski was a Haredi Rabbi born in 1883 in Warsaw , Poland and died in 1944 in Kovna , Lithuania .
Rachel Davis Harris ( May 10 , 1869 -- 1969 ) was an American librarian and activist .
Danny Halloran ( 4 July 1954 -- 17 February 2012 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Carlton in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Vilas Sarang ( Devanagari : विलास सारंग ) ( 1942 - 2015 ) is one of the most significant modernist Indian writers , critics and translators to emerge in the post - independence period .
Aristodimos Kaldis ( August 15 , 1899 , in Dikeli , Asia Minor , Turkey -- 1979 ) was an artist and left - wing activist in New York .
Mehmet Cemaleddin Efendi ( 1848 - -1917 ) ( Turkish : Mehmet Cemâlüddin Efendi ) was a senior judge of the Ottoman Empire .
Clifford Morris ( died November 1944 ) , better known as Mighty Destroyer was a Trinidadian calypsonian who won the Calypso King contest in 1941 .
Augustus Frederic Rudolf Hoernlé ( often Hoernle ) , CIE ( 1841 - -1918 ) was a German - British Orientalist .
Thomas William Hogarth ( Kelso , 6 April 1901 -- 26 January 1999 ) was a Scottish , later Australian , veterinarian , writer on dogs , dog judge , dog breeder , genetics enthusiast and veterinary surgeon .
Hale Asaf , originally Salih ( 1905 , Istanbul - 31 May 1938 , Paris ) was a Turkish painter of Georgian and Circassian ancestry .
John Ewart Beswick ( 5 April 1897 -- February 1978 ) was an English footballer who played in the Football League for Stoke .
Hasan Rıza ( 1857 - -1913 ) was an Ottoman painter , soldier , and government official .
Captain Thomas James Young VC ( 1827 -- 20 March 1869 ) was a recipient of the Victoria Cross , the highest and most prestigious award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and Commonwealth forces .
Nils Strandell ( 20 May 1876 - 20 or 28 July 1963 ) was a Swedish philatelist who signed the Roll of Distinguished Philatelists in 1922 .
Brian Spillett GC ( 1937 - 16 January 1965 ) was posthumously awarded the George Cross , the highest British ( and Commonwealth ) award for bravery out of combat .
Sir Philip Shelbourne ( born 15 June 1924 -- 15 April 1993 ) was a British lawyer and financier .
Samuel Asare Konadu ( 18 January 1932 -- 1994 ) was a Ghanaian journalist , novelist and publisher , who also wrote under the pseudonym Kwabena Asare Bediako .
George Mealmaker ( 10 February 1768 -- 30 March 1808 ) was a Scottish radical organiser and writer , born in Dundee , Scotland .
Toivo Pohjala ( 1 February 1888 -- 23 August 1969 ) was a Finnish wrestler and harness racing driver .
Howard Harry Rosenbrock ( 16 December 1920 -- 21 October 2010 ) was a leading figure in control theory and control engineering .
Idalia Anreus ( 1932 -- January 3 , 1998 ) was a Cuban actress who worked in both theatre and film .
Augustus Gough - Calthorpe , 6th Baron Calthorpe ( 8 November 1829 -- 22 July 1910 ) was a British agriculturist and philanthropist .
Yevgeniy Ivchenko ( Russian : Евгений Ивченко , Belarusian : Яўген Іўчанка ; 26 June 1938 in Sumy Oblast , Ukrainian SSR -- 2 June 1999 ) was a Soviet athlete who competed mainly in the 50 km walk .
Robert Parys ( died 1408 ) , of Hildersham , Cambridgeshire , was an English politician .
Charles Robert Barry QC , PC ( 3 January 1823 -- 15 May 1897 ) was an Irish lawyer who rose to become a Lord Justice of Appeal for Ireland .
Kewal Singh ( 1915 - -1991 ) was an Indian diplomat , Foreign Secretary and India 's ambassador to the USSR , Pakistan and USA .
Robert Jankel ( 1 January 1938 -- 25 May 2005 ) was a British designer of limousines , armoured cars and other speciality vehicles .
Peter Hagner ( b. in Philadelphia , Pa. , 1 Oct. , 1772 ; d. in Washington , D. C. , 16 July 1850 ) was a financier and United States civil servant .
Francis Talfourd ( also Frank ) ( 1828 - -1862 ) was an English barrister , known as a dramatist .
Fireman Frederick Davies ( 17 February 1913 -- 23 August 1945 ) of the British National Fire Service was posthumously awarded the George Cross , the highest British ( and Commonwealth ) award for bravery out of combat .
Shardha Ram Phillauri ( 30 September 1837 -- 24 June 1881 ) was a Hindu missionary , social reformer , astrologer , and writer , best remembered for his contributions to Hindi and Punjabi literature .
François Bouffier ( 1844 - -1881 ) was a French non - commissioned officer of the 19th century , a sergeant of the 8th Battalion of infantrymen .
Paul Poulet ( 1887 - -1946 ) was a self - taught Belgian mathematician who made several important contributions to number theory , including the discovery of sociable numbers in 1918 .
Ludwig - Wilhelm Tepper de Ferguson ( Lewis - William Ferguson - Tepper , Tepper von Ferguson , Louis - Guillaume Tepper de Ferguson ; 18 December 1768 , Warsaw -- 12 September 1838 , Paris ) was a Polish--
Patrick Ruthven , 1st Earl of Forth and 1st Earl of Brentford ( c. 1573 -- 2 February 1651 ) was a Scottish nobleman , general , and diplomat .
Henry Dodwell ( October 1641 -- 7 June 1711 ) was an Anglo - Irish scholar , theologian and controversial writer .
Thomas Passhe ( died 1489 ) was a Canon of Windsor from 1449 to 1489 .
Hermanus Numan ( 1744 - -9 March 1820 ) was a Dutch painter , draftsman , pastellist , etcher , engraver , watercolorist , set painter , decorator ( interiors ) , art theorist , and publisher .
Marshall Brement ( born 10 January 1932 in New York City - died on 6 April 2009 in Tucson , Arizona ) was a career United States Foreign Service officer , who served as United States Ambassador to Iceland in 1981 - 1985 and after retirement was a professor at the University of Virginia .
Ulpius Limenius ( died 8 April AD 349 ) was a Roman politician who was appointed consul in AD 349 .
Karol Grossmann ( 27 October 1864 -- 3 August 1929 ) was a pioneering film maker in the Austro - Hungarian Empire .
Nicholas Lynch ( c. 1590 - 1634 ) , Dominican priest and prior of Galway .
Aagot Nissen ( née Kavli ; 1882 -- 1978 ) was a Norwegian actress .
Ahmed Mejjati ( born in Casablanca in 1936 - 1995 ) was an influential Moroccan avant - garde poet .
Jens Jørgen Thorsen ( 2 February 1932 Holstebro -- 15 November 2000 ) was a Danish artist , director , and jazz musician whose works sometimes created controversy .
Robert M. Wilkinson ( April 11 , 1921 -- September 27 , 2010 ) was a political figure and lobbyist in the San Fernando Valley in California .
James Milnor Coit ( January 31 , 1845 - -1925 ) was an American teacher , born in Harrisburg , Pennsylvania .
Wilhelm von Krosigk ( 1871 - 1953 ) , was the German commander of the SMS Stettin .
Sara Hammond ( 1672 -- May 1716 ) was a Norwegian landowner and businesswoman .
Basil Hadley ( 1940 in London , England -- 2006 in Stepney , Adelaide ) was an English Australian printmaker and painter .
Emmanuel - Marie Blain de Saint - Aubin ( 30 June 1833 -- 9 July 1883 ) was an educator , song - writer , story - teller , and translator .
Sir Thomas Hanmer , 4th Baronet ( 24 September 1677 -- 7 May 1746 ) was Speaker of the House of Commons from 1714 to 1715 , discharging the duties of the office with conspicuous impartiality .
Samuel Walker ( 1714 - -1761 ) , called Samuel Walker of Truro , was an English evangelical clergyman of the Church of England .
Les Carr ( 22 May 1929 -- 11 May 2012 ) was a former Australian rules footballer who played with Carlton in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Samuel Crompton ( 3 December 1753 -- 26 June 1827 ) was an English inventor and pioneer of the spinning industry .
Manuel da Luz Afonso ( Loulé , 31 January 1917 - 15 October 2000 ) was a Portuguese football manager .
Peter Stokes ( died 1399 ) was an English Carmelite friar , known as an opponent of the teachings of John Wyclif .
Enrica Calabresi ( 10 November 1891 Ferrara -- 20 January 1944 ) was an Italian zoologist , herpetologist , and entomologist .
Niels Wulfsberg ( 29 August 1775 -- 25 June 1852 ) was a Norwegian priest , newspaper editor and publisher .
Khosrow IV was a Sasanian usurper who ruled briefly in 631 .
Zhao Xi ( simplified Chinese : 赵憙 ; traditional Chinese : 趙憙 ; pinyin : Zhào Xǐ ; 4 - 80 CE ) , courtesy name Boyang ( simplified Chinese : 伯阳 ; traditional Chinese : 伯陽 ; pinyin : Bóyáng ) , was a politician who lived in the early Eastern Han Dynasty .
Jens Schou Fabricius ( 3 March 1758 -- 6 April 1841 ) was the Norwegian appointed Minister of the Navy 1817 - -1818 .
Afonso , Prince of Portugal ( Portuguese pronunciation : ( ɐˈfõsu ) ; 18 May 1475 -- 13 July 1491 ) - was the heir apparent to the throne of Portugal .
Otar Koberidze ( Georgian : ოთარ კობერიძე ; 17 December 1924 -- 9 March 2015 ) was a Georgian actor , film director and screenwriter .
John Savile , 3rd Earl of Mexborough ( 3 July 1783 -- 25 December 1860 ) , styled Viscount Pollington until 1830 , was a British peer and Tory politician .
Patri Fidiel ( 1762 - -1824 ) was a Capuchin , author of poems about religious aspects and with a popular traditional versification .
John Ayldon ( 11 December 1943 -- 16 February 2013 ) was an English opera singer and comic actor , best known for his performances in bass - baritone roles of the Savoy Operas with the D'Oyly Carte Opera Company .
Wing Gillette ( died 8 September 1996 ) was a West Indian cricket umpire .
Fumo Madi ibn Abi Bakr was Sultan of Pate , Kenya ( 1779 - 1809 ) .
Wang Daohan ( Chinese : 汪道涵 ; pinyin : Wāng Dàohán ) , ( 27 March 1915 -- 24 December 2005 ) was the former president of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits ( ARATS ) .
Max Schur ( 26 September 1897 -- 12 October 1969 ) was a physician and friend of Sigmund Freud .
Isaac Wilkinson ( baptised 6 May 1695 - 31 January 1784 ) was an English industrialist , one of the founders of the iron industry and pioneer of the Industrial Revolution .
Mattie Clarke ( 1922 in Dublin -- 6 January 1960 ) was a soccer player from Dublin , Ireland .
Charles Townshend Murdoch ( 27 May 1837 -- 8 July 1898 ) was a banker and Conservative politician who sat in the House of Commons between 1885 and 1898 .
William Cochrane , 1st Earl of Dundonald ( 1605 - - November 1685 ) supported the Royalist cause during the Wars of the Three Kingdoms .
Luca Penni ( c.1500/1504 - -1556 ) was an Italian painter of the 16th century best known for his work in France as part of the School of Fontainebleau .
Elizabeth Creed ( née Pickering ; 1642 - -1728 ) was a daughter of Sir Gilbert Pickering , Bart . , cousin to the poet John Dryden , and a second cousin to Samuel Pepys .
Brian G. Hughes ( 1849 - -1924 ) was a US businessman and practical joker .
Fran Ramovš ( 14 September 1890 -- 16 September 1952 ; pen name Julij Dub ) was a Slovenian linguist .
Mrs. Pack ( died 1694 ) was a wet nurse to the child William , Duke of Gloucester ( 1689 - -1700 ) ; she was believed indispensable to the boy 's health , and because of that , came to exercise considerable control over the household of his mother , the future Queen Anne .
Diarmaid mac Madudan , Chief of Síol Anmchadha 1032 - 1069 .
Lady Augusta Gordon ( née FitzClarence ; 17 November 1803 -- 8 December 1865 ) was a British noblewoman .
Alessandro Rolla ( Italian pronunciation : ( alesˈsandro ˈrɔlla ) ; 22 April 1757 -- 15 September 1841 ) was an Italian viola and violin virtuoso , composer , conductor and teacher .
Sebastian Newdigate , O.Cart . , ( 7 September 1500 -- 19 June 1535 ) was the seventh child of John Newdigate , Sergeant - at - law .
Amir Sultan ( 1368 - -1429 ) was Amir Kulal Shamsuddin 's grandson .
Igor Dvornik ( 9 May 1923 , Split - 21 August 2010 , Zagreb ) was a Croatian radiation chemist .
N.L. Peschier ( died after 1661 ) , was a Dutch Golden Age painter .
Zhou Shidi ( Chinese : 周士第 ; Pinyin : Zhōu Shìdì ; 1900 - -1979 ) was a general of the People 's Liberation Army of China .
Kavi Kunjara Bharati ( 1810 - -1896 ) was a Tamil poet and a composer of Carnatic music .
Adam Marsh ( Adam de Marisco ) ( c. 1200 -- 18 November 1259 ) was an English Franciscan , scholar and theologian .
Mirko Beljan ( 12 October 1899 -- 14 October 1959 ) was an Ustaše officer in the Independent State of Croatia during World War II . He was born in the village of Dobrići , near Tomislavgrad .
Alexandros Vasileiou ( Greek : Αλέξανδρος Βασιλείου , 1760 - -1818 ) was a Greek merchant and scholar , one of the representatives of the modern Greek Enlightenment .
Clara Birnberg ( 1894 - -1989 ) was an Anglo - Jewish artist , illustrator , portraitist and sculptor .
Adelaide Caroline Johanne Brun ( known as Ida Brun and later as Ida ( de ) Bombelles ; 20 September 1792 -- 23 November 1857 ) was a Danish singer , dancer , and classical mime artist in the genre known as mimoplastic art or `` attitude '' .
André - Joseph Exaudet ( 1710 - -1762 ) was a French violinist and composer , best known for composing the influential 1751 minuet bearing his name .
Hans Brenaa ( b Copenhagen , 9 October 1910 , d Copenhagen , 14 April 1988 ) was a Danish dancer , teacher , and ballet director .
Lorentz Johannsen ( 14 September 1769 -- 27 April 1837 ) was a Norwegian merchant and member of the Norwegian Parliament .
George Collison ( 1772 - -1847 ) was an English Congregationalist and educator associated with Hackney Academy or Hackney College , which became part of New College London -- itself part of the University of London .
Som Nath Sadhu ( 1935 - 1982 ) was an Indian theatre personality known for his contributions to Kashmiri theatre as an actor , playwright and director .
Llywarch ap Llywelyn ( fl . 1173 - -1220 ) was a medieval Welsh poet .
Najeeb Diab had five daughters and a son , and died in Brooklyn , New York on 11 July 1936 .
Francesco Stelluti ( 12 January 1577 -- November 1652 ) was an Italian polymath who worked in the fields of mathematics , microscopy , literature , and astronomy .
Allan Campbell McLean ( 1922 - - 1989 ) was a British writer and political activist .
Ouyang Xun ( Chinese : 歐陽詢 ; Wade -- Giles : Ou - yang Hsun ) ( 557 - -641 ) , courtesy name Xinben ( 信本 ) , was a Confucian scholar and calligrapher of the early Tang Dynasty .
Abune Paulos ( 3 November 1935 -- 16 August 2012 ) was Patriarch of the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church ( 1992 - -2012 ) .
Daniel Casper ( 25 January 1635 , Nimptsch , Niederschlesien -- 28 April 1683 , Breslau , Niederschlesien ) , also spelled Daniel Caspar , and referred to from 1670 as Daniel Casper von Lohenstein , was a Baroque Silesian playwright , lawyer , diplomat , poet , and chief representative of the Second Silesian School .
Henrietta Adler ( 1 December 1868 -- 15 April 1950 ) , known as Nettie Adler , was a Jewish Liberal Party politician who was one of the first women to be elected and to be able to take her seat on the London County Council .
The 3rd Jebtsundamba Khutughtu ( 1758 - 1773 ) , was the third incarnation of the Jebtsundamba Khutuktu , the spiritual heads of the Gelug lineage of Tibetan Buddhism in Mongolia .
Konstantin Sarajev ( Constantine Saradjian ) ( 1877 - -1954 ) was a Soviet Armenian conductor and violinist .
Yosef Serlin ( Hebrew : יוסף סרלין‎ , 24 February 1906 -- 15 January 1974 ) was a Zionist activist , lawyer and Israeli politician .
Marija Petković , also known as `` The Blessed Mary of Jesus Crucified Petković '' ; ( Croatian : Marija od Propetoga Isusa Petković , Italian Maria Di Gesù Crocifisso ) , ( 10 December 1892 - 9 July 1966 ) was the founder of the Catholic Congregation of the Daughters of Mercy .
Luchetto Gattilusio ( fl . 1248 - -1307 ) was a Genoese statesman , diplomat , and man of letters .
Edward Rishton ( 1550 -- 29 June 1585 ) was an English Roman Catholic priest .
Pavel Solomirsky ( Russian : Павел Дмитриевич Соломирский ; 1801 - -1861 ) was a business magnate in the Russian Empire , the member of the wealthy Turchaninov family , which originated from a Turk prisoner Philip Turchaninov .
Prince Michał Jerzy Poniatowski , born Michał Jerzy Poniatowski ( 12 October 1736 -- 12 August 1794 ) was a Polish nobleman .
Arnold Moll ( 5 May 1675 -- 10 February 1729 ) was the Dutch commander of Jaffanapatnam from 1723 to 1725 and acting Governor of Ceylon from 21 June 1723 to 12 January 1724 .
Agnes Waterhouse ( c. 1503 - 29 July 1566 ) , also known as Mother Waterhouse , was the first woman executed for witchcraft in England .
Alfred Weidler ( né Alfred Wilhelm Carl Weidler 27 May 1886 Georgsmarienhütte , Germany -- 16 June 1966 Los Angeles ) was an architect who , after moving from Germany to Los Angeles in 1923 , went on to became a prolific model builder for 40 years with 20th Century Fox .
Dame Mary V. Austin ( née Hall - Thompson ; 29 July 1900 -- 10 September 1986 ) was an Australian community worker and political activist .
John Poynder ( 1779 - -1849 ) was an English lawyer and theological writer , best known for his Literary Extracts and as a proponent of Christian missions in India
Alan Hellary ( 29 August 1923 -- 28 August 1992 ) was a British pilot who co - founded British Atlantic Airways , which would later become Virgin Atlantic Airways .
Joseph Harb ( 1940 -- 9 February 2014 ) was a Lebanese poet and writer .
Joan Kerr ( 1938 - 2004 ) was an Australian academic and cultural preservationist .
Captain Henry Ross ( 1829 -- 5 December 1854 ) was a Canadian gold miner at Ballarat , Victoria , Australia , and was known on the goldfields as the ' bridegroom ' of the miners flag , the Southern Cross , the Eureka Flag .
General John Campbell , 4th Earl of Loudoun ( 5 May 1705 -- 27 April 1782 ) was a British nobleman and army officer .
John Rodker ( 18 December 1894 -- 6 October 1955 ) was a British writer , modernist poet , and publisher of modernist writers .
Hulü Guang ( 斛律光 ) ( 515 - -572 ) , courtesy name Mingyue ( 明月 ) , was a general of the Chinese dynasty Northern Qi .
Kathleen Eaton Cannell ( usually known as Kitty Cannell ) ( 1891 -- 1974 ) was a Paris - based American dance and fashion correspondent for major U.S. papers and periodicals .
Sir John Bussy ( died 29 July 1399 ) of Hougham in Lincolnshire was a Member of Parliament representing Lincolnshire or Rutland eleven times from 1383 to 1398 as a Knight of the Shire .
Hermann Schridde ( 3 July 1937 in Celle - 18 May 1985 in Meißendorf near Winsen ) was a German equestrian .
Thøger Birkeland ( 20 March 1922 -- 6 April 2011 ) was a Danish teacher and writer mostly known for his children 's books .
Allen Hill ( 14 November 1843 , Kirkheaton , Huddersfield , Yorkshire -- 28 August 1910 , Leyland , Lancashire ) played in the first - ever cricket Test , taking the first wicket .
Sir Henry Strachey , 1st Baronet ( 23 May 1736 -- 3 January 1810 ) was a British civil servant and politician .
Walter Harrison Cady ( 1877 - -1970 ) was an American illustrator and author , best known for his Peter Rabbit comic strip which he wrote and drew for 28 years .
James Hinton ( baptized 26 November 1822 -- died 16 December 1875 ) was an English surgeon and author .
Norman J. Hunt ( died 1984 ) was a composer , conductor , arranger , and performer in the big band era , covering a wide range of musical styles including classical music , jazz , and was a featured soloist on many recordings and performances globally .
Karmabai ( 20 January 1615 -- 1634 ) was a Jat known as- Bhakt Shiromani Karmabai .
Balthasar de Beaujoyeulx ( also Balthasar de Beaujoyeux ) , originally Baldassare de Belgiojoso ( d. ca . 1587 , Paris ) was an Italian violinist , composer , and choreographer .
E. Imre Friedmann ( 1921 -- June 11 , 2007 ) was a biologist , Robert O. Lawton Distinguished Professor of Biology at Florida State University and the NASA Ames Research Center , and Director , Polar Desert Research Center .
Scot Young ( 1962 -- 2014 ) was a Scottish property tycoon .
Kang Dae - ha ( April 12 , 1942 -- 1995 ) was a South Korean screenwriter , producer , film and art director and poet .
Sir Thomas Nicholas Redington KCB ( 2 October 1815 -- 11 October 1862 ) was an Irish administrator , politician and civil servant .
Paluzzo Paluzzi Altieri degli Albertoni ( 8 June 1623 -- 29 June 1698 ) was an Italian Catholic Cardinal and Cardinal - Nephew to Pope Clement X.
Franjo Majetić ( 26 February 1923 -- 29 November 1991 ) was a Croatian actor noted for his comedic roles .
Nathaniel Pilch ( born 4 September 1793 in Brisley , Norfolk ; died 1881 in Erpingham , Norfolk ) was an English first - class cricketer associated with Norfolk who was active from 1820 to 1836 .
Muhammad ibn Ahmed ibn Muhammad ' Illish ( 1802 - 1882 CE ) ( 1217 - 1299 AH ) ( Arabic : محمد بن أحمد عليش‎ ) , more commonly referred to in Muslim works simply as ' Illish or Sheikh ' Illish , was a 19th - century CE Egyptian Muslim jurist from Tripolitanian origin .
Zhuge Shuang ( 諸葛爽 ) ( d. 886 ) was a general of the Chinese dynasty Tang Dynasty , who controlled Heyang Circuit ( 河陽 , headquartered in modern Jiaozuo , Henan ) for some time and who vacillated between allegiance to Tang and to the Qi state of the agrarian rebel Huang Chao .
Kirsten Heiberg ( 25 April 1907 -- 2 March 1976 ) was a Norwegian actress and singer who had a major film career in Germany between 1938 and 1954 .
George Bornoff ( 5 November 1907 -- 1998 ) was a Canadian violinist and string teacher .
Sun Tongxuan ( 孙桐萱 ; Sun Tung - hsuan ; 1895 - -1978 ) was a Kuomintang general .
Jack Horrigan ( December 30 , 1925 -- June 2 , 1973 ) was a sportswriter for the Buffalo Evening News and American Football League ( AFL ) Public Relations Director who went on to serve in public relations for the Buffalo Bills .
Sir Tannatt William Edgeworth David , KBE , CMG , DSO , FRS , ( 28 January 1858 -- 28 August 1934 ) , professionally known as Edgeworth David , was a Welsh Australian geologist and Antarctic explorer .
Mordechai Efraim Fischel Sofer - Zussman ( 1867 - -1942 ) was a prominent rabbi who served in various communities before becoming the head if the Yere'im Community and chief rabbi of Budapest , Hungary in 1914 .
Abdul Latif Chowdhury ( Bengali : আব্দুল লতিফ চৌধুরী ; 25 May 1913 -- 16 January 2008 ) , widely known as Saheb Qiblah Fultali , was a Bangladeshi Islamic scholar of theology , philosophy , murshid , spiritual esotericist , and spiritual leader .
Robert Younger , Baron Blanesburgh GBE PC QC ( 12 September 1861 -- 17 August 1946 ) was a Scottish barrister and judge .
Krushnaji Prabhakar Khadilkar ( Devanagari : कृष्णाजी प्रभाकर खाडिलकर ) ( 1872 - -1948 ) was a Marathi writer from Maharashtra , India .
Samuel Wesley ( 24 February 1766 -- 11 October 1837 ) was an English organist and composer in the late Georgian period .
Lady Katherine Sophia Kane ( née Baily ; 11 March 1811 -- 25 February 1886 ) was an Irish botanist , best known for her book on Irish flowering plants The Irish Flora ( 1833 ) .
Field Marshal John Campbell , 5th Duke of Argyll ( June 1723 -- 24 May 1806 ) , styled Marquess of Lorne from 1761 to 1770 , was a Scottish soldier and nobleman .
Frederick Leypoldt ( 17 November 1835 , in Stuttgart , Germany -- 31 March 1884 , in New York City ) was a bibliographer , the founder of Library Journal , Publisher 's Weekly , Index Medicus and other publications .
John Trundle ( 1575 - 1629 ) was a London publisher and bookseller .
Sir Denis Follows , CBE ( 13 April 1908 -- 17 September 1983 ) was a British sports administrator .
Giacomo Orefice ( 27 August 1865 -- 22 December 1922 ) was an Italian composer .
Neokosmos Grigoriadis ( Greek : Νεόκοσμος Γρηγοριάδης , 1879 - -1967 ) was a Greek Army general , notable for his involvement in the Greek Resistance during World War II as a leading member of the left - wing National Liberation Front ( EAM ) .
Lloyd Powell ( 22 August 1888 -- 25 March 1975 ) was an English , later Canadian pianist and teacher .
Pope Gregory X ( Latin : Gregorius X ; c. 1210 -- 10 January 1276 ) , born Teobaldo Visconti , was Pope from 1 September 1271 to his death in 1276 and was a member of the Secular Franciscan Order .
Frankie Walsh ( 1936 -- 28 December 2012 ) was an Irish hurler who played as a left wing - forward for the Waterford senior team .
Ganapati Chakraborty ( Bengali : গণপতি চক্রবর্তী ) ( 1858 - 20 November 1939 ) was an magician from Kolkata known for his mesmerizing tricks .
Alfred Cellier ( 1 December 1844 -- 28 December 1891 ) was an English composer , orchestrator and conductor .
Marshall Ho'o ( 1910 - 1993 ) was an American practitioner of t'ai chi ch'uan .
Ernest George Harcourt Williams ( 30 March 1880 -- 13 December 1957 ) was an English actor and director .
Guy Stewart Callendar ( February 1897 - October 1964 ) was an English steam engineer and inventor .
James Rewcastle ( c.1802 - -1867 ) was the first secretary of the Newcastle Temperance movement , and a songwriter born in the Newcastle area .
Herbert B. Fredersdorf ( 2 October 1899 -- 21 July 1971 ) was a German film editor , screenwriter and film director .
Rothad of Soissons ( died 869 ) was Bishop of Soissons .
Joseph Barret ( 1665 - -1699 ) was an English businessman and theological writer .
Zoltán Kemény ( 21 March 1907 - 14 June 1965 ) was a sculptor .
John McNeil Eddings ( born 1830 , died 1896 ) was the military storekeeper at Fort Vancouver , and a prominent civic leader of Clark County in what was then the Washington Territory .
Nehemiah Guthridge ( c.1808 - 27 June 1878 ) , was an Irish - born Melbourne ironmonger , a city councillor in Melbourne , a parliamentarian representing the Central Province ( November 1856 to August 1858 ) in the Legislative Council , a prominent Wesleyan and the first mayor of Sale in 1863 .
S. Kalitheerthan ( died January 2011 ) was an Indian politician and former Member of the Legislative Assembly of Tamil Nadu .
Jay Robert McColl ( March 24 , 1867 - 1936 ) was the dean of Engineering for University of Detroit starting in 1911 .
Julius Braun ( 16 July 1825 , Karlsruhe -- 1869 , Munich ) was a German historian , with an interest in art , culture and religion .
Elizabeth Moody ( 1737 Kingston upon Thames - 1814 ) was a British poet , and literary critic .
Peter Coupar ( 17 October 1866 -- 6 July 1944 ) was a Scottish footballer who played for Dundee and Stoke .
Pushpa Sundar Tuladhar ( 1885 - 1935 ) was a prominent merchant of Kathmandu and one of the chief donors to the restoration of the Swayambhu stupa in 1918 .
Elva Nampeyo ( 1926 - -1985 ) ( also known as Elva Tewaguna ) was an American studio potter .
Helena Argyre or Argyropoulaina ( Greek : Ἑλένη Ἀργυρή/Ἀργυροπούλαινα , Georgian : ელენე , elene ) ( died c. 1033 ) was a Byzantine noblewoman of the Argyros family and Queen Consort of Georgia as the first wife of King Bagrat IV of the Bagratids .
Begum Om Habibeh Aga Khan ( 15 February 1906 -- 1 July 2000 ) was the fourth and last wife of Sir Sultan Muhammad Shah , Aga Khan III . The couple married thirteen months after the Aga Khan III and his third wife were divorced by mutual consent .
Manaji Rao Gaekwad ( before April 1751 -- 27 July 1793 ) was the Maharaja of Baroda ( r.1789 - -1793 ) .
David Kantilla ( traditional name Amparralamtua 1938 or 1940 - -1978 ) was an Australian rules footballer who is recognised as the first Indigenous Australian to play in the South Australian National Football League and the first Tiwi Islander to successfully play in a southern football league .
Jiří Grossmann ( 20 July 1941 -- 5 December 1971 ) was a Czechoslovak theatre actor , poet , and composer .
Hubert Henry Davies ( 17 March 1869 -- 17 August 1917 ) was a leading British playwright and dramatist of the early twentieth century , following in the tradition of Arthur Wing Pinero and Henry Arthur Jones , but influenced profoundly by Thomas William Robertson .
Augustus Henry Keane ( 1833 - -1912 ) was an Irish Roman Catholic journalist and linguist , known for his ethnological writings .
Hugh McCartney ( 3 January 1920 -- 28 February 2006 ) was a Scottish Labour politician .
Ngô Đức Kế ( 1878 - -1929 ) was a prominent scholar - gentry Vietnamese anti - colonial intellectual in the early 20th century .
Leonard Mociulschi ( Romanian pronunciation : ( le.oˈnard moˈt͡ʃjul.ski ) ) ( 27 March 1889 , Siminicea , Botoşani County in northern Moldavia - 15 April 1979 , Braşov ) was a Romanian Major General during World War II .
Dame Joan Bartlett , S.S.I. , O.B.E. , D.S.G. , ( 1 August 1911 , Lancashire -- 9 September 2002 ) was a prominent British convert to the Roman Catholic Church and the foundress of the Servite Secular Institute .
John Lethbridge ( 1675 - -1759 ) invented the first underwater diving machine in 1715 .
Michael Abercrombie FRS ( 14 August 1912 -- 28 May 1979 ) was a British cell biologist and embryologist .
Samuel Antek ( 1909 - -1958 ) was a violinist in the NBC Symphony Orchestra under conductor Arturo Toscanini .
George Hazlett ( 10 March 1923 -- 21 December 2012 ) was a Scottish footballer who played as an outside right in the Football League .
Henry Dornan ( 14 February 1916 - 4 December 1990 ) was a Scottish footballer who played for Kilmarnock and made ' guest ' appearances during the Second World War for Dumbarton and Celtic .
Welf VII ( c. 1135 -- 11 or 12 September 1167 ) was the only son of Welf VI , Duke of Spoleto and Margrave of Tuscany , and Uta , daughter of Godfrey of Calw , count palatine of the Rhine .
Louis Morizot ( 1874 - -1957 ) was an influential French bow maker of great reputation .
DJ Subroc ( August 3 , 1973 -- April 23 , 1993 ) was an English - born American hip hop artist and a member of KMD and Constipated Monkey .
Robert de Eglesfield ( c.1295 - 1349 ) , 1341 founder of The Queen 's College , Oxford , and a chaplain of Queen Philippa of Hainault in whose honour he named the college .
Jan Ruhtenberg ( a.k.a . Alexander Gustaf Jan Ruhtenberg or Alexander Gustav Jan Ruhtenberg , born Alexander Gustaf Rutencrantz von Ruhtenberg , 28 February 1896 -- died , December 1975 ) was an architect who `` made significant contributions in introducing modern architecture to the United States as a teacher and a modern architect '' .
Alfred Arthur Greenwood Hales ( 21 July 1860 -- 29 December 1936 ) was an Australian novelist and war correspondent .
Sir Walter Farquhar , 1st Baronet ( October 1738 -- 30 March 1819 ) was a prominent Scottish physician of the late eighteenth and early nineteenth century , whose clientele included many of the leading figures of the day , including the Prince of Wales ( later King George IV ) and the Prime Minister William Pitt .
William Attersoll ( died 1640 ) , was an English puritan divine and author .
Cecil Raleigh ( 27 January 1856 -- 10 November 1914 , London , England ) was an English actor and playwright .
Willie Edouin ( 1 January 1846 -- 14 April 1908 ) was an English comedian , actor , dancer , singer , writer , director and theatre manager .
Bekim Fehmiu ( 1 June 1936 -- 15 June 2010 ) was a Yugoslavian theater and film actor of Albanian ethnicity .
Hatibzade Yahya Pasha ( known by contemporaries as just Yahya Pasha ; died August 1755 ) was an Ottoman statesman and admiral .
Barend Bonneveld ( 27 November 1887 -- 9 February 1978 ) was a Dutch heavyweight wrestler .
Samuel Claridge ( December 5 , 1828 -- September 11 , 1919 ) was a member of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter - day Saints ( LDS Church ) who was a prominent early settler of the Muddy River Valley in Nevada and Thatcher , Arizona .
Venmani S. Selvanather ( 6 July 1913 -- 14 October 1993 ) was the Archbishop of the Archdiocese of Pondicherry and Cuddalore from 1973 - 1992 succeeding Ambrose Rayappan .
Israel Eldad ( Hebrew : ישראל אלדד ) ( 11 November 1910 -- 22 January 1996 ) , was an Israeli Revisionist Zionist philosopher and member of the pre - state underground group Lehi .
Everard des Barres ( also Eberhard von Barres or Eberhard De Bären ) ( died 1174 ) was the third Grand Master of the Knights Templar from 1147 to 1151 .
Lloyd Hunter ( May 4 , 1910-month and date unknown , 1961 ) was an African - American trumpeter and big band leader from North Omaha , Nebraska .
Flann Ó Tighearnaigh ( IPA:(ˈfˠl̪ˠaːn̪ˠoːˈtʲɪjəɾˠn̪ˠiː ) ) , Gaelic - Irish Lord , died 1273 .
Percy Weston ( 27 March 1852 -- 30 June 1905 ) was an English amateur athlete who played for England in two of the unofficial football matches against Scotland in 1871 and 1872 .
Larry L'Estrange MBE ( 12 November 1934 -- 29 March 2007 ) was a British soldier and London Irish rugby player .
Baruch Epstein or Baruch ha - Levi Epstein ( 1860 - -1941 ) ( Hebrew : ברוך הלוי אפשטיין ) was a Lithuanian rabbi , best known for his Torah Temimah commentary on the Torah .
Kirkman Finlay ( April 1773 -- 4 March 1842 ) was one of the leading merchants in Glasgow , Scotland .
Vincenzo Jannacci ( 3 June 1935 -- 29 March 2013 ) , more commonly known as Enzo Jannacci ( Italian pronunciation : ( ( vintʃ)ˈɛntso janˈnattʃi ) ) , was an Italian singer - songwriter , actor and stand - up comedian .
Aquila Nebeker ( 1859 - -1933 ) was the president of the Utah Senate during its second term .
Sir Brooke Boothby , 6th Baronet ( 3 June 1744 -- 23 January 1824 ) was a linguist , translator , poet and landowner , based in Derbyshire , England .
Princess Deokhye of Korea ( 25 May 1912 -- 21 April 1989 ) was the last princess of Korea .
Geoffrey Barkas ( born Geoffrey de Gruchy Barkas , 27 August 1896 -- 3 September 1979 ) was an English film maker active between the world wars .
Maharaja Hari Singh Dhillon ( died 1764 ) , was a Dhillon Jat , founder of Bhangi Misl was one of the most powerful , admired and famous of all the royal Sikh warriors of the 18th century .
Lee Sun - Fung ( born 10 April 1909 in Guangdong , China , died 21 May 1985 ) was a Chinese film director , writer and actor .
Jack Sirocco ( 1882 - 1954 ) was a New York gangster involved in labor racketeering and strikebreaking .
Hermann Ludwig von Balan ( born 7 March 1812 in Berlin , died 16 March 1874 in Brussels ) was a German diplomat who served as acting Foreign Secretary and head of the Foreign Office from 1872 to 1873 .
Prince Eugen of Bavaria ( German : Eugen Leopold Adelaide Thomas Maria Prinz von Bayern ) ( 16 July 1925 -- 1 January 1997 ) was a member of the Bavarian Royal House of Wittelsbach .
Henry Cadogan Rothery ( 1817 -- 2 August 1888 ) was an English lawyer and commissioner of wrecks ( now known as the Receiver of Wreck ) , especially remembered for chairing the inquiry into the Tay Bridge disaster in 1879 .
Antonio Manganelli ( 8 December 1950 -- 20 March 2013 ) was an Italian police chief , and head of Polizia di Stato from June , 2007 , when he replaced Gianni De Gennaro .
Richard Hageman ( 9 July 1881 -- 6 March 1966 ) was a Dutch - born American conductor , pianist , composer , and actor .
William Harris Lloyd Roberts ( 31 October 1884 -- 28 June 1966 ) was a Canadian writer , poet , and playwright .
Richard Dawson ( born Colin Lionel Emm ; 20 November 1932 -- 2 June 2012 ) was a British - American actor and comedian , and a game show host and panelist in the United States .
Alexander Kerst ( 23 February 1924 -- 9 December 2010 ) was an Austrian television actor .
Sir Alexander Bannerman ( 7 October 1788 -- 30 December 1864 ) was a British merchant , vintner , politician and colonial governor .
Lee Ki - poong ( 20 December 1896 - 28 April 1960 ) was a South Korean politician and Vice President .
Ernest Collins ( 1851 -- 20 April 1914 ) was a British water supply engineer .
Robert Munford III ( 1737 - 1783 ) was an American playwright , civic leader and soldier , having served under Colonel George Washington in the French and Indian War and later serving in the Revolutionary War .
Nicholas de Balscote ( died 1320 ) was an English - born official and judge in fourteenth - century Ireland : he achieved high office , but his career was ruined by a quarrel with King Edward II .
Śīlabhadra ( Sanskrit ; traditional Chinese : 戒賢 ; pinyin : Jièxián ) ( 529 - -645 ) was a Buddhist monk and philosopher .
Frederick II , Duke of Saxe - Gotha - Altenburg ( 28 July 1676 , in Gotha -- 23 March 1732 , in Altenburg ) , was a duke of Saxe - Gotha - Altenburg .
Richard Arthur ( 25 October 1865 -- 21 May 1932 ) was an Australian politician , social reformer and medical practitioner .
Mahmud Mahmud ( Persian : محمود محمود‎‎ ; 1881 - -1965 ) was an Iranian politician and historian .
Martin McQuade ( 19 October 1894 -- 6 February 1957 ) was an Australian rules footballer who played with Melbourne in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Laurence Harvey ( born Laruschka Mischa Skikne ; 1 October 1928 -- 25 November 1973 ) was a Lithuanian - born South African actor .
Cleph ( also Clef , Clepho , or Kleph ) was king of the Lombards from 572 to 574 .
Francisco de Mora ( c.1553 - -1610 ) was a Spanish Renaissance architect .
Margaret Russell , Baroness Ampthill , GCVO , CI , GBE , DStJ ( 8 October 1874 -- 12 December 1957 ) was the daughter of the 6th Earl Beauchamp .
Albert Titley ( 18 November 1918 -- 17 September 1986 ) was an English footballer who played for West Bromwich Albion , Port Vale , and Macclesfield Town in the 1930s .
Matteo de ' Medici ( 9 May 1613 -- 14 October 1667 ) was the brother of Ferdinand II , Grand Duke of Tuscany .
Pandit Puttaraj Gawai ( Kannada : ಪುಟ್ಟರಾಜ ಗವಾಯಿ ) ( 3 March 1914 -- 17 September 2010 ) was an Indian musician in the Hindustani classical tradition , a scholar who authored more than 80 books in Kannada , Sanskrit and Hindi , a music teacher and a social servant .
Sir Thomas Thwaites or Thwaytes ( c.1435 - -1503 ) was an English civil servant , who was involved in the Perkin Warbeck conspiracy .
Heinz Fenchel ( 1906 - -1988 ) was a German art director , who designed the sets for a number of films in Weimar Germany and Czechoslovakia .
Karen Horney ( /ˈhɔrnaɪ/ ; born Danielsen , 16 September 1885 -- 4 December 1952 ) was a German psychoanalyst who practiced in the United States during her later career .
Shalom Shachna ( died 1558 ) was a rabbi and Talmudist , and Rosh yeshiva of several great Acharonim including Moses Isserles , who was also his son - in - law .
Lew Bloom ( August 8 , 1859 -- December 12 , 1929 ) was an American vaudeville performer and stage actor who popularized the comical tramp character .
Jonče Hristovski ( Macedonian : Јонче Христовски ) ; ( Bitola , 1931 - Skopje , 5 April 2000 ) was a Macedonian singer and composer of folk music .
Radu Gioan Bey ( 1613 Iaşi -- 1660 ) , was a Prince of Moldavia .
Barnaba Tortolini ( 19 November 1808 -- 24 August 1874 ) was a 19th - century Italian priest and mathematician who played an early active role in advancing the scientific unification of the Italian states .
Joseph Bartlett Eastman ( June 26 , 1882 -- 1944 ) was a member of the Interstate Commerce Commission from 1919 until his death in 1944 .
Chinua Achebe ( /ˈtʃɪnwɑː əˈtʃɛbɛ/ , born Albert Chinualumogu Achebe ; 16 November 1930 -- 21 March 2013 ) was a Nigerian novelist , poet , professor , and critic .
Johannes Fedé ( also Jean Sohier ) ( c. 1415 -- 1477 ? ) was a French composer of the early Renaissance .
Reid Miles ( 4 July 1927 -- 2 February 1993 ) was an American graphic designer and photographer best known for his iconic work for Blue Note Records in the 1950s and ' 60s .
Étienne Lucier ( June 9 , 1786 -- March 8 , 1853 ) was a fur trader in the Pacific Northwest .
Wei Gao ( 韋皋 ) ( 745 -- September 13 , 805 ) , courtesy name Chengwu ( 城武 ) , formally Prince Zhongwu of Nankang ( 南康忠武王 ) , was a general of the Tang dynasty of China .
Dinanath Mishra ( or Dina Nath Mishra , 1937 - 2013 ) was an Indian journalist and writer belonging to the Hindu nationalist movement .
Bruno II of Isenburg - Braunsberg was the Count of Isenburg - Braunsberg from 1210 until 1255 .
Arthur Cleghorn ( 1 December 1873 -- 7 May 1951 ) was an Australian rules football player at the Essendon Football Club in the Victorian Football League ( VFL ) .
Bartholomaeus of Bruges ( Barthélemy de Bruges ) ( died 1356 ) was a Flemish physician and natural philosopher .
Ndugu M’Hali or Kalulu ( ca . 1865 -- 28 March 1877 ) was an African personal servant and adopted child of the explorer and journalist Henry Morton Stanley .
John Stratford , 1st Earl of Aldborough ( c. 1691 -- 29 May 1777 ) was an Irish peer and politician .
Avraham Kalfon ( Hebrew : אברהם כלפון‎ , born 16 December 1900 , died 4 July 1983 ) was an Israeli politician who served as a member of the Knesset for Mapai between 1952 and 1955 .
Dracula Unleashed is a 1993 video game created by ICOM Simulations and published by Viacom for the Sega CD , Apple Macintosh and DOS platforms .

Windows Embedded Compact , formerly Windows Embedded CE and Windows CE , is an operating system subfamily developed by Microsoft as part of its Windows Embedded family of products .

Star Warrior is a 1980 science fiction role - playing video game written and published by Automated Simulations ( later known as Epyx ) for the Apple II , TRS-80 , and Atari home computers .
The Watermelon is an independent feature film penned by Michael Hemmingson and directed by Brad Mays .

The Singer Not the Song is a 1961 British drama film based on the 1953 novel by Audrey Erskine - Lindop that was directed by Roy Ward Baker and filmed in Spain .

The San Pietro Polyptych ( Italian : Polittico di San Pietro ) is a polyptych by Italian Renaissance master Perugino , painted around 1496 - -1500 .
Dual Plover is a pioneering independent Australian record label , founded in Sydney in 1996 , notable for discovering some of the most enigmatic artists in experimental music .
Big Japan Pro Wrestling ( BJW ) is a Japanese professional wrestling promotion established in 1995 .
The North Sea Commission is an international organization founded in 1989 .
Northeastern Bible College was founded by Charles W. Anderson and first opened in September , 1950 , as Brookdale Bible School , at the Brookdale Baptist Church in Bloomfield , New Jersey .
Cidade Negra ( Portuguese : Black City ) is a Brazilian reggae band formed in 1986 in Rio de Janeiro .
On his initiative the Thuringian federal government established the Stiftung Ettersberg , located in Weimar , as a foundation under civic law , which took up its work in spring 2002 by the appointment of the executive board and the advisory council of the foundation .
Biocon was founded in 1978 with ₹10,000 as the initial capital , failing to find any financial institution for investment .
GoEast is an International Film Festival which has been held annually in the Hessian state capital of Wiesbaden , Germany since its inception in 2001 .
Etisalat was founded in 1976 as a joint - stock company between International Aeradio Limited , a British Company , and local partners .
Necromance was a Christian gothic metal band from Spremberg , Germany , formed in 1987 , disbanded in 2002 .
Commonwealth Credit Union was founded on April 2 , 1951 with $ 2,700 in assets and 122 members .
Wigrid is an underground black metal project that was founded by Ulfhednir in 1998 .
The Empowering Spirits Foundation was established by A. Latham Staples in 2008 after the passage of Proposition 8 in California out of frustration as to how he thought LGBT rights organizations were approaching the gay rights issue .
The Ankara Metro , has been operating since 29 December 1997 , with the opening of its first full metro line , M1 , traveling between Kızılay , the city center , and Batıkent .
The Party of Reform and Development ( PRD ) ( Arabic : حزب الاصلاح والتنمية Hizb Al - Islah Wal - Tanmiyah ) is a political party in Libya , that was founded on 10 January 2012 in Benghazi .
Ant - Zen Audio and Visual Arts is a German independent record label founded in 1994 by Stefan Alt ( aka recording artist S.Alt ) , who serves as the art director .
Dagö was formed in 1998 by Lauri Saatpalu , Peeter Rebane and Tiit Kikas .
Pueblo a Pueblo is a 501(c ) organization launched in 2001 to provide educational opportunities for children in rural Mayan communities in Guatemala .
The Wichita Falls Spudders were a minor league baseball team that formed in 1920 and played its last game in 1957 .
The Webb Brothers are a rock band from Chicago , Illinois , who formed in 1998 .
The State of Thuringia was restored with slightly altered borders during Germany 's reunification in 1990 .
The Carter Family was a traditional American folk music group that recorded between 1927 and 1956 .
USAA was founded in 1922 by a group of U.S. Army officers as a mechanism for mutual self - insurance when they were unable to secure auto insurance because of the perception that they , as military officers , were a high - risk group .
Originally formed in 1931 as Sakaryaspor , the club changed its name to Manisaspor on 15 June 1965 .
Salmon Air is a former commuter airline based in Salmon , Idaho , United States which was established in 1968 .
The Nationalist Party of Cantabria ( Spanish : Partido Nacionalista de Cantabria , PNC ) was a political party with a nationalist and conservative ideology active in Cantabria between 1988 and the mid 90s .
Founded in Atlanta , Georgia in 1984 , Lauren Engineers & Constructors started as a small specialty non - union contractor and subsidiary of Comstock Mechanical .
The Melbourne Science Fiction Club Inc. ( Also known as the M.S.F.C. or colloquially `` the club '' ) was founded in May 1952 by Race Mathews and others .

Bruno Fortichiari ( February 8 , 1892 - January 4 , 1981 ) was an Italian politician and communist revolutionary .
Nicla Vassallo ( born 1963 ) , is an Italian philosopher with research and teaching interests in epistemology , philosophy of knowledge , theoretical philosophy , as well as feminist philosophy .
Luís André de Pina Cabral e Villas - Boas ( Portuguese pronunciation : ( luˈiʃ ɐ̃ˈdɾɛ dɨ ˈpinɐ kɐˈbɾaɫ i ˈviɫɐʒ ˈboɐʃ ) ; born 17 October 1977 ) , known as André Villas - Boas , is a Portuguese football manager who is the current manager of Russian club Zenit Saint Petersburg .
Paolo Roversi ( born 1947 ) is an Italian - born fashion photographer who lives and works in Paris .
Ernest Thiel 's parents were the Belgian Catholic engineer Jacques Thiel and Fanny Stiebel , of German - Jewish origin .
Vadim Zeland ( Rus . Вадим Зеланд ) is a contemporary Russian mystic and writer .
Sir William Dugdale ( 12 September 1605 -- 10 February 1686 ) was an English antiquary and herald .
Jonathan Stephen Ross , OBE ( born 17 November 1960 ) is an English television and radio presenter , film critic , and actor best known for presenting the BBC One chat show Friday Night with Jonathan Ross during the 2000s .
More of his published writings are listed at Friedrich Hiebel in German Wikipedia and at German National Library .
Leonardo Polo ( February 1 , 1926 -- February 9 , 2013 ) was a renowned Spanish philosopher best known for his philosophical method called abandonment of the mental limit and the profound philosophical implications and results of the application of this method .
Alethea Lewis ( born 19 December 1749 , buried 12 November 1827 ) was an English novelist , born at Acton , near Nantwich , Cheshire .
Mathias - Marie Duval ( 7 February 1844 -- 28 February 1907 ) was a French professor of anatomy and histology born in Grasse .
Samuel Musgrave , FRS ( 29 September 1732 -- 5 July 1780 ) was an English classical scholar and physician .
Józef Maria Hoene - Wroński ( French : Josef Hoëné - Wronski ; originally Josef Hoëné ; 23 August 1776 -- 9 August 1853 ) was a Polish Messianist philosopher , mathematician , physicist , inventor , lawyer , and economist .
Iván Pozo ( born 26 August 1979 , Vigo , Spain ) is a retired Spanish professional boxer .
Kristín Helga Gunnarsdóttir ( born November 24 , 1963 ) is an Icelandic children 's writer .
Alphonse Roque - Ferrier ( 1 August 1844 -- 18 June 1907 ) was a French philologist and historian of the occitan language .
Fuad Jorge Jury ( 28 May 1938 -- 5 November 2012 ) , commonly known as Leonardo Favio ( Spanish pronunciation : ( leoˈnarðo ˈfaβjo ) ) , was an Argentine singer , actor , film director and screenwriter .
Imre Trencsényi - Waldapfel ( Budapest , 16 June 1908 - Budapest , 3 June 1970 ) , was a Hungarian classical scholar , and member of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences .
Blessed Louis - Édouard Cestac ( 6 January 1801 - 27 March 1868 ) was a French Roman Catholic priest and was the co - founder of the Servants of Mary .
Stefan Banach ( ( ˈstɛfan ˈbanax ) ; 30 March 1892 -- 31 August 1945 ) was a Polish mathematician who is generally considered one of the world 's most important and influential 20th - century mathematicians .
İsmail Cem ( born İsmail Cem İpekçi , 15 February 1940 -- 24 January 2007 ) was a Turkish politician , journalist , statesman and minister of foreign affairs .
John Lewis Brown ( 1829 -- 1890 ) was a French battle , animal , and genre painter .
Rachid Driss ( Arabic : الرشيد إدريس ) ( January 27 , 1917 -- September 5 , 2009 ) was a Tunisian diplomat and writer .
Shulim or Nikolai Aleksandrovich Notovich ( Николай Александрович Нотович ) , known in the West as Nicolas Notovitch ( 1858-after 1916 ) was a Crimean Jewish adventurer who claimed to be a Russian aristocrat and journalist .
Hans Christian Lumbye ( Danish pronunciation : ( lɔmˈbyː ) ; 2 May 1810 -- 20 March 1874 ) was a Danish composer of waltzes , polkas , mazurkas and galops , among other things .
Julius Stinde ( 28 August 1841 -- 5 August 1905 ) , German author , was born at Kirchnüchel in Holstein , the son of a clergyman .
Johann Karl Friedrich Rosenkranz ( April 23 , 1805 -- July 14 , 1879 ) was a German philosopher and pedagogue .
Edward Aldam Leatham ( 2 August 1828 -- 6 February 1900 ) was an English Liberal Member of Parliament .
Lorenzo Bernal del Mercado ( 1530 - -1593 ) was a Spanish captain who was one of the more successful soldiers in the Arauco War in Chile rising to the rank of Maestre de Campo and temporary Capitán General of the Captaincy General of Chile .
Walter Flex ( 6 July 1887 -- 16 October 1917 ) was a German author responsible for Der Wanderer zwischen beiden Welten ( The Wanderer between Two Worlds ) , a war novel dealing with themes of humanity , friendship , and suffering during World War I.
Georg Heinrich von Görtz , Baron of Schlitz ( 1668 -- February 19 , 1719 ) , diplomat in Swedish service , was born in Holstein and educated at Jena .
Jean - Pierre Rives ( born 31 December 1952 ) is a French champion rugby player and visual artist .
Amancio Amaro Varela , ( born 16 October 1939 in A Coruña , Galicia ) commonly known simply as Amancio , is a former Spanish football player .
Luc Foisneau , born in Blois on the 30th March 1963 , is a French philosopher specialising in contemporary political thought and that of the Early Modern period .
Jakob van Hoddis ( May 16 , 1887 in Berlin -- 1942 in Sobibor ) was the pen name of a German - Jewish expressionist poet Hans Davidsohn , of which name `` Van Hoddis '' is an anagram .
Gottschalk Eduard Guhrauer ( 15 May 1809 -- 5 January 1854 ) was a German philologist and biographer .
Friedrich August Moritz Retzsch ( December 9 , 1779 - June 11 , 1857 ) was a German painter , draughtsman , and etcher .
Helena Dahlbäck ( 1960 - -2000 ) was a Swedish author who wrote several children 's books , for example My Sister Lotta and Me .
Gert Wingårdh ( born 1951 ) is a Swedish architect whose company , Wingårdh arkitektkontor , maintains an international practice .
Sergio Blanco Rivas ( 17 November 1948 -- 15 February 2015 ) and Estíbaliz Uranga Amézaga ( or Estíbaliz Uranga ; born 9 December 1952 ) , known professionally as Sergio y Estíbaliz , were a Spanish vocal duo , who also worked with groups Mocedades and El Consorcio .
François Boissier de Sauvages de Lacroix ( May 12 , 1706 - -February 19 , 1767 ) was a French physician and botanist who was a native of Alès .
John Fane , 7th Earl of Westmorland ( 24 March 1685 -- 26 August 1762 ) , styled The Honourable John Fane from 1691 to 1733 and Lord Catherlough from 1733 to 1736 , was an English nobleman and soldier .
Count Burkhard Christoph von Münnich ( 9 May 1683 -- 16 October 1767 ) ( Христофо́р Анто́нович Миних ) was a German soldier - engineer who became a field marshal and political figure in the Russian Empire .
William Murray , 1st Earl of Mansfield , SL , PC ( 2 March 1705 -- 20 March 1793 ) was a British barrister , politician and judge noted for his reform of English law .
Sir Basil Henry Liddell Hart ( 31 October 1895 -- 29 January 1970 ) , commonly known throughout most of his career as Captain B. H. Liddell Hart , was an English soldier , military historian and military theorist .
Noël du Fail , seigneur de La Hérissaye ( c.1520 - -1591 ) was a French jurist and writer of the Renaissance .
Rudolf Steinwand ( 4 August 1906 -- 10 November 1982 ) was a German politician ( KPD , SED ) .
Camille Bulcke ( 1 September 1909 -- 17 August 1982 ) was a Belgian Jesuit missionary in India , who attained pre - eminence in the Hindi language and came to be known as `` India 's most famous Christian Hindi scholar '' .
Klaus G. Troitzsch ( * 28 . November 1946 , in Ilsede - Oberg , Lower Saxony ) is a German sociologist .
Anthony Cave Brown ( March 21 , 1929 in Bath - July 14 , 2006 in Warrenton , Virginia ) was an English - American journalist , espionage non - fiction writer , and historian .
Juan Tomás Ávila Laurel ( born 1966 in Santa Isabel , Spanish Guinea - now Malabo , Equatorial Guinea ) is an Annobonese writer from Equatorial Guinea .
Leone Ginzburg ( Italian : ( leˈone ˈɡintsburɡ ) ; 4 April 1909 -- 5 February 1944 ) was an Italian editor , writer , journalist and teacher , as well as an important anti - fascist political activist and a hero of the resistance movement .
Sir William John Newton ( 1785 - -1869 ) was an English miniature - painter , in fashion in the early part of the 19th century .
Vincenz Priessnitz , also written Prießnitz ( sometimes in German Vinzenz , in English Vincent , in Czech Vincenc ; 4 October 1799 -- 26 November 1851 ) was a peasant farmer in Gräfenberg , Austrian Silesia , who is generally considered the founder of modern hydrotherapy , which is used in alternative and orthodox medicine .
Daniela Hodrová ( born 5 July 1946 ) is a Czech writer and literary scholar .
Roy Carr is an English music journalist .
Renzo De Felice ( 8 April 1929 -- 25 May 1996 ) was an Italian historian , who specialized in the Fascist era , writing - among others - a 6000-page biography of Mussolini ( 4 volumes , 1965 - -97 ) .
Joan Orpí i del Pou , also Juan Orpín or Juan Urpín ( 1593 in Piera -- 1 July 1645 in Barcelona , Venezuela ) was a Spanish conquistador , known for founding New Barcelona in Venezuela , and for founding the short - lived Province of New Catalonia ( 1633 - -1654 ) .
Frank Hornby ( 15 May 1863 -- 21 September 1936 ) was an English inventor , businessman and politician .
Raquel Sánchez - Silva ( born 13 January 1973 in Plasencia , Cáceres , Spain ) is a Spanish television conductor and journalist .
Kate Sedley is the pen - name of Brenda Margaret Lilian Honeyman Clarke , an English historical novelist .
Louis - Maurice Boutet de Monvel ( 18 October 1850 -- 16 March 1913 ) was a French painter and illustrator best known for his watercolors for children 's books .
Karuna Banerjee ( Bengali : করুণা ব্যানার্জী ) ( December 25 , 1919 -- November 13 , 2001 ) was a Bengali actress best known for her role in Satyajit Ray 's The Apu Trilogy ( 1955 - -1959 ) as the long suffering mother , Sarbajaya .
Vittoria Accoramboni ( 15 February 1557 -- 22 December 1585 ) was an Italian noblewoman .
Oscar Ribeiro de Almeida Niemeyer Soares Filho ( December 15 , 1907 -- December 5 , 2012 ) , known as Oscar Niemeyer ( Brazilian Portuguese : ( ɔʃˈkaʁ ˈniemajeʁ ) ) , was a Brazilian architect who is considered to be one of the key figures in the development of modern architecture .
John Ord ( 1729?--1814 ) was an English barrister and politician .

Bruno Villabruna ( 1884 - 1971 ) was an Italian lawyer and liberal politician .

Antun Mihanović ( 1796 - 1861 ) was a notable Croatian poet and lyricist , most famous for writing the national anthem of Croatia , which was put to music by Josif Runjanin and adopted in 1891 .
Werner Veigel ( 9 November 1928 -- 2 May 1995 ) was a Dutch - born German journalist and news presenter .
Marcel - Auguste Dieulafoy ( August 3 , 1844 - February 25 , 1920 ) was a French archaeologist , noted for his excavations at Susa ( modern - day Shush , Iran ) in 1885 and for his work , L'Art antique de la Perse .
Robert Copland ( fl . 1515 ) , English printer and author , is said to have been a servant of William Caxton , and certainly worked for Wynkyn de Worde .
Uriel Ofek ( Hebrew : אוריאל אופק , born : 30 June 1926 in Tel Aviv -- 23 January 1987 ) was an Israeli writer for children and youth , editor , lyricist , poet , translator and children 's literature scholar .
Luo Niansheng ( simplified Chinese : 罗念生 ; traditional Chinese : 羅念生 ; pinyin : Luó Niànshēng ; 12 July 1904 - 10 April 1990 ) was a Chinese translator .
Leelo Tungal ( born 22 June 1947 in Tallinn ) is an Estonian poet , children 's literature author , editor and librettist .
Sten Nadolny , ( born 29 July 1942 , in Zehdenick , Province of Brandenburg ) is a German novelist .
Tie Ning ( simplified Chinese : 铁凝 ; traditional Chinese : 鐵凝 ; pinyin : Tiě Níng ; Wade -- Giles : T'ieh Ning ; born September 1957 ) is a Chinese author based in Beijing , China .

Neal Asher ( born 4 February 1961 in Billericay , Essex , England ) is an English science fiction writer .
Naomi Chazan ( Hebrew : נעמי חזן‎ , born 18 November 1946 ) is an Israeli academic , activist , and politician .
Johann Sommer ( Latin : Ioannes Sommerus ; 1542 - -1574 ) was a Transylvanian Saxon Protestant theologian , poet and Despot Vodă 's biographer .
Giuseppe D'Agata ( 11 January 1927 -- 29 March 2011 ) was an Italian author , screenwriter and television writer .

Juan de la Cruz Mourgeón y Achet ( died April 1822 in Quito ) was a Spanish general and colonial administrator .
Guglielmo Libri Carucci dalla Sommaja ( January 1 , 1803 -- September 28 , 1869 ) was an Italian count and mathematician , who became known for his love and subsequent theft of ancient and precious manuscripts .
Henry of Settimello ( in Latin , Henricus Septimellensis or Henricus Pauper ; in Italian , Arrigo or Arrighetto da Settimello ) was a late 12th - century Italian poet .

Gonzalo Argote de Molina ( 1548 - -1596 ) was a Spanish writer , historian and genealogist .

Jacques - Arsène d'Arsonval ( June 8 , 1851 -- December 31 , 1940 ) was a French physician , physicist , and inventor of the moving - coil D'Arsonval galvanometer and the thermocouple ammeter .
Giuseppe Arcimboldo ( Italian : ( dʒuˈzɛppe artʃimˈbɔldo ) ; also spelled Arcimboldi ) ( 1526 or 1527 -- July 11 , 1593 ) was an Italian painter best known for creating imaginative portrait heads made entirely of objects such as fruits , vegetables , flowers , fish , and books .
Christian August Gottlob Eberhard ( 12 January 1769 -- 13 May 1845 ) was a German miscellaneous writer .
Ulrich Thein ( 4 July 1930 -- 21 June 1995 ) was a German actor film director and screenwriter .

Julius Plücker ( 16 June or 16 July 1801 -- 22 May 1868 ) was a German mathematician and physicist .
Zygmunt Kubiak ( 30 April 1929 , Warsaw -- 19 March 2004 ) was a Polish writer , essayist , translator , propagator of the antique culture , and professor at the University of Warsaw .
Charles Harvey Combe ( February 1863-August 1935 ) was a Conservative Member of Parliament from 1892 and 1897 for the English constituency of Chertsey .

Károly Marót ( Arad , 2 March 1885 - Budapest , 27 October 1963 ) , was a Hungarian classical scholar , philologist and member of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences .
Johann Friedrich Pfaff ( sometimes spelled Friederich ; 22 December 1765 -- 21 April 1825 ) was a German mathematician .
Gabriel Sundukian ( Armenian : Գաբրիել Սունդուկյան ; 11 July 1825 - 29 March 1912 ) was an Armenian writer and playwright , the founder of modern Armenian drama .
Stefan Lochner ( the Dombild Master or Master Stefan ) ( c. 1410 - -1451 ) was a German painter working in the late `` soft style '' of the International Gothic .
Cristóbal Martín de Herrera ( Aldeadávila de la Ribera , Spain , 20 March 1831 - Madrid , Spain , 1878 ) was a Spanish politician who served as Ministry of Public Works in the reign of Alfonso XII .
Nehemiah Wallington ( 1598 -- 1658 ) was an English Puritan artisan ( a wood turner ) and chronicler .
Willi Sänger ( 21 May 1894 in Berlin , Germany - 27 November 1944 in Brandenburg , Germany ) was a German Communist and resistance fighter against the Nazis .
Bartomeu Rosselló - Pòrcel ( Catalan pronunciation : ( bərtuˈmɛw rusəˈʎo ˈpɔrsəɫ ) ) ( 3 August 1913 in Palma , Majorca -- 5 January 1938 in El Brull , Barcelona ) was a Spanish Balearic poet , who wrote in Catalan .
Josep Maria Bayarri i Hurtado ( Valencian pronunciation : ( dʒuˈzɛb maˈɾi.a βaˈjari ) ) ( Alboraya ( Valencia ) , Spain , 1886 - 1970 ) was a writer and poet , also known as Xusep Maria Vaiarri .
Percy Wyndham Lewis ( 18 November 1882 -- 7 March 1957 ) was an English painter and author ( he dropped the name ' Percy ' , which he disliked ) .
From his consulting work and media presence , Michel Rolland has influenced many aspects of both the French and global wine industry .
Vincenzo Cerami ( 2 November 1940 -- 17 July 2013 ) was an Italian screenwriter , novelist and poet .
Toni Acosta ( La Orotava , Santa Cruz de Tenerife , 10 April 1972 ) is a Spanish actress .
Yosef Haim Brenner ( Hebrew : יוסף חיים ברנר‎ , also Yosef Chaim Brenner , 1881 - -1921 ) was a Russian - born Hebrew - language author and one of the pioneers of modern Hebrew literature .
Jan Kochanowski ( Polish : ( ˈjan kɔxaˈnɔfskʲi ) ; 1530 -- 22 August 1584 ) was a Polish Renaissance poet who established poetic patterns that would become integral to the Polish literary language .
Sebastian de Aparicio y del Pardo , O.F.M. , was a Spanish colonist in Mexico shortly after its conquest by Spain , who after a lifetime as a rancher and road builder entered the Order of Friars Minor as a lay brother .
Peter Ludwig Mejdell Sylow ( IPA : ( ˈsyːlɔv ) ) ( 12 December 1832 -- 7 September 1918 ) was a Norwegian mathematician who proved foundational results in group theory .
Eugen Drewermann ( born 20 June 1940 ) is a German church critic , theologian , peace activist and former Roman Catholic priest .
Angelo Oliviero Olivetti ( 1874 -- 17 November 1931 ) was an Italian lawyer , journalist , and political activist .
Juan de Herrera ( 1530 -- 15 January 1597 ) was a Spanish architect , mathematician and geometrician .
Pierre du Calvet ( 1735 -- March 28 , 1786 ) was a Montreal trader , justice of the peace , political prisoner and epistle writer of French Huguenot origin .
Samson Raphael Hirsch ( June 20 , 1808 -- December 31 , 1888 ) was a German rabbi best known as the intellectual founder of the Torah i m Derech Eretz school of contemporary Orthodox Judaism .
Nirmal Verma ( Devanāgarī : निर्मल वर्मा ; 3 April 1929 -- 25 October 2005 ) was a Hindi writer , novelist , activist and translator .
Macarena Gómez Traseira ( born 2 February 1978 ) is a Spanish actress , known for her role of Lola in the current television series La que se avecina , aired on Telecinco .
Stamp Brooksbank ( 1694 -- 24 May 1756 ) was an English MP and Governor of the Bank of England .
Robert Gerhard i Ottenwaelder ( Catalan pronunciation : ( ruˈβɛrd ʒəˈɾart ) ; 25 September 1896 -- 5 January 1970 ) was a Catalan composer and musical scholar and writer , generally known outside Catalonia as Roberto Gerhard .
Zhang Xianliang ( Chinese : 张贤亮 ; December 1936 -- 27 September 2014 ) was a Chinese author and poet , and former president of the China Writer Association in Ningxia .
Patrick Marnham is an English writer , journalist and biographer .
Charles - Robert Ageron ( 6 November 1923 -- 3 September 2008 ) was a French historian specializing in colonial Algeria .
Wolfram Saenger ( born 1939 ) is a German biochemist and protein crystallographer .
Attila Kotányi ( Hungarian : ( ˈɒtilːɒ ˈkotaːɲi ) ; 1924 , Hungary -- 18 October 2003 , Düsseldorf ) was a poet , philosopher , writer and architect - urbanist .
Armand Thomas Hue de Miromesnil ( 15 September 1723 - 6 July 1796 ) was a minister of the French Ancien Régime who served as Keeper of the Seals under Louis XVI .
Albert Hotopp ( 20 September 1886 -- 1 August 1942 ) was a German political activist and writer .
Arthur Bingham Walkley ( 17 December 1855 -- 7 October 1926 ) , usually known as A B Walkley was an English public servant and drama critic .
Zigmantas Balčytis ( born 16 November 1953 in Šilutė district municipality ) is a Lithuanian politician who briefly served as acting Prime Minister of Lithuania in 2006 .
Agnete Friis ( born 1974 ) is a Danish writer who is best known for co - authoring Drengen i kufferten , or The Boy in the Suitcase .
Casimir Davaine ( March 19 , 1812 -- 14 October 1882 ) was a French physician known for his work in the field of microbiology .
Iwasa Matabei ( Japanese : 岩佐 又兵衛 ; original name Araki Katsumochi 1578 -- July 20 , 1650 ) was a Japanese artist of the early Tokugawa period ( 1603 - -1867 ) , who specialized in genre scenes of historical events and illustrations of classical Chinese and Japanese literature , as well as portraits .
Ilvo Diamanti ( born Cuneo , September 4 , 1952 ) is an Italian political scientist .

Tore Zetterholm ( 1915 - -2001 ) was a Swedish novelist , playwright and journalist .
François Michel de Rozière ( 29 September 1775 , Melun - 4 November 1842 , Melun ) was a French mining engineer .
Simon Atumano was the Bishop of Gerace in Calabria from 23 June 1348 until 1366 and the Latin Archbishop of Thebes thereafter until 1380 .
Christiaan Huygens , FRS ( /ˈhaɪɡənz/ or /ˈhɔɪɡənz/ ; Dutch : ( ˈɦœy̆ɣə(n)s ) ) ( Latin : Hugenius ) ( 14 April 1629 -- 8 July 1695 ) was a prominent Dutch mathematician and scientist .
Mildred Archer OBE ( 28 December 1911 in London -- 4 February 2005 ) was an English art historian who specialized in 18th- and 19th - century art in British India .
Tamara Milosevic ( born 1976 in Frankfurt am Main ) is a German documentary filmer of Serbian descent .
Theophanes the Greek ( sometimes `` Feofan Grek '' from the Russian : Феофан Грек , Greek : Θεοφάνης ; c. 1340 -- c. 1410 ) was a Byzantine Greek artist and one of the greatest icon painters of Muscovite Russia , and was noted as the teacher and mentor of the great Andrei Rublev .
William Coare Brocklehurst ( 9 February 1818 -- 3 June 1900 ) was an English Liberal Party politician and head of a family of silk producers in Macclesfield in the 19th century .

A. C. Zainuddin ( 12 May 1952 -- 4 November 1999 ) was a popular Malayalam film comedian actor .
Johannes Helms ( 8 November 1828 -- 4 December 1895 ) was a Danish writer and schoolmaster who experienced the Three Years ' War firsthand .

Benedetto Castelli ( 1578 -- 9 April 1643 ) , born Antonio Castelli , was an Italian mathematician .

Marcos Jiménez de la Espada ( 1831 - -1898 ) was a Spanish zoologist , herpetologist , explorer and writer , born in Cartagena , Spain , although he spent most of his life in Madrid , where he died .
Christian Frederik Møller ( 31 October 1898 -- 5 November 1988 ) , generally referred to as C. F. Møller , was a Danish architect , professor and , from 1965 to 1969 , the first rector of the Aarhus School of Architecture .
Philippe Renaud ( born November 23 , 1962 ) is a French sprint canoer who competed during the 1980s .
Charles Fairfax Murray ( 1849 -- 1919 ) , was an English painter , dealer , collector , benefactor and art historian who was intimately connected with the second wave of the Pre - Raphaelites .

Jean - Jacques Gaspard Foelix ( 1791 - -1853 ) was a French jurist and the founder of the science of comparative law in France .
Jeremy Brock ( born 1959 ) is an English writer , and director whose works include the screenplays Mrs. Brown , Driving Lessons , The Last King of Scotland , Charlotte Gray and The Eagle .
Jean - Mandé Sigogne ( 6 April 1763 -- 9 November 1844 ) was a French Catholic priest , who moved to Canada after the Revolution and became known for his missionary work among the Acadians of Nova Scotia .
Jean - Marie Camille Guérin ( 22 December 1872 -- 9 June 1961 ) was a French veterinarian , bacteriologist and immunologist who , together with Albert Calmette , developed the Bacillus Calmette - Guérin ( BCG ) , a vaccine for immunization against tuberculosis .
Santiago Cervera Soto ( Pamplona , Spain , 27 March 1965 ) was a Spanish politician who belonged to the People 's Party ( PP ) of Navarre .
Ernesto Buonaiuti ( 1881 -- 1946 ) was an Italian historian , philosopher of religion , Catholic priest and anti - fascist .
Francisco Espoz Ilundáin ( 17 June 1781 -- 24 December 1836 ) , being better known as Francisco Espoz y Mina , was a Spanish guerrilla leader and general .
Florence Arthaud ( 28 October 1957 -- 9 March 2015 ) was a French sailor from Boulogne - Billancourt .

KIJV ( 1340 AM ) is a radio station licensed to serve Huron , South Dakota .
WBBB ( `` Radio 96.1 '' ) , is an adult hits radio station based in Raleigh , North Carolina , owned by Curtis Media Group .

WDDW ( 104.7 FM ) is a Spanish language radio station licensed to Sturtevant , Wisconsin , and serving the Milwaukee and Racine area .
WGHT ( 1500 AM ) is a radio station licensed to serve Pompton Lakes , New Jersey , USA .
WFHG - FM is a Talk formatted broadcast radio station licensed to Bluff City , Tennessee and serving the Tri - Cities region of Tennessee and Virginia .
WSHY is a radio station licensed to Lafayette , Indiana , USA , located at 1410 kHz on the AM dial .

WMGN ( 98.1 FM , `` Magic 98 '' ) is a radio station licensed to and serving the Madison , Wisconsin area .
The Mitsubishi Concept - RA is a concept car manufactured by Mitsubishi Motors , and first revealed on at the North American International Auto Show in January 2008 .
The SIG P210 ( Swiss Army designation Pistole 49 ) is a locked breech semi - automatic pistol designed and manufactured in Neuhausen am Rheinfall ( Canton of Schaffhausen , Switzerland ) by Swiss Arms AG , formerly SIG Arms AG ( distributed in U.S. by SIGARMS ) .
The GWR 1101 Class was a class of 0 - 4 - 0 T side tank steam locomotives built by the Avonside Engine Company to the order of the Great Western Railway in 1926 for dock shunting .
The Sharp PC-5000 was a pioneering laptop computer , announced by Sharp Corporation of Japan in 1983 .

Texas Instruments produces a range of calculators , with the TI-30 being one of the most popular early calculators .
The MAC-10 ( Military Armament Corporation Model 10 , officially the M-10 ) is a compact , blowback operated machine pistol developed by Gordon B. Ingram in 1964 .

Seward .

In Greek mythology Phrixus ( /ˈfrɪksəs/ ; also spelt Phryxus ; Greek : Φρίξος , Phrixos ) was the son of Athamas , king of Boeotia , and Nephele ( a goddess of clouds ) .
The Wurm is a left ( western ) tributary of the River Rur ( Roer River ) .
The Niobrara River ( /ˌnaɪ.əˈbrærə/ ; from the Ponca Ní Ubthátha khe pronounced ( nĩꜜ ubɫᶞaꜜɫᶞa kʰe ) , meaning `` water spread - out horizontal - the '' ) is a tributary of the Missouri River , approximately 568 miles ( 914 km ) long , running through the U.S. states of Wyoming and Nebraska .
The Kuta River is a Siberian river north of Lake Baikal in Irkutsk Oblast , Russia , that flows into the Lena River at Ust - Kut .
The Medjerda River ( Tunisian Arabic : واد مجردا‎ ) is a river in North Africa flowing from northeast Algeria through Tunisia before emptying into the Gulf of Tunis and Lake of Tunis .
The Lubefu River is a tributary of the Sankuru River , which in turn is a tributary of the Kasai River in the Democratic Republic of the Congo .
The Shashe River ( or Shashi River ) is a major left - bank tributary of the Limpopo River in Zimbabwe .
For the moment , Ankara River is a tributary of the Sakarya River .
The Sormitz is a subsidiary stream of the Loquitz in Thuringia , Germany and is 29.2 km in length .
The Similkameen River runs through southern British Columbia , Canada , eventually discharging into the Okanogan River near Oroville , Washington in the United States .
The Chambal River is a tributary of the Yamuna River in central India , and thus forms part of the greater Gangetic drainage system .
Bulstake Stream , also spelt Bullstake Stream , is a backwater of the River Thames at Oxford , England .
The Rába ( German : Raab ; Hungarian : Rába ; Slovene : Raba ( ˈráːba ) ; Prekmurian : Rába ) is a river in southeastern Austria and western Hungary and a right tributary of the Danube .
The Little Snake River is a tributary of the Yampa River , approximately 155 miles ( 249 km ) long , in southwestern Wyoming and northwestern Colorado in the United States .
The Monocacy River is a free - flowing left tributary to the Potomac River , which empties into the Atlantic Ocean via the Chesapeake Bay .
The Jari River , or Jary River ( Portuguese : Rio Jari ) , is a northern tributary of the Amazon River on the border between the states of Pará and Amapá in northeastern Brazil .
The Bâlea River is a headwater of the Cârțișoara River in Romania .
The Hāwea River is a river of New Zealand , draining Lake Hāwea into the Clutha River .
Trześniówka is a river in Poland , a right tributary of the Vistula ( near the city of Sandomierz ) .
The Kabompo River is one of the main tributaries of the upper Zambezi River river .
Queens Pound River rises on the northern slopes of the Kybeyan Range within Wadbilliga National Park , southwest of the locality of Yowrie and flows generally north and northwest , before reaching its confluence with the Wadbilliga River near the locality of Wadbilliga .
The river flows generally south then south by west and then south , joined by the five tributaries including the Caledonia River East Branch ( which is also joined by the Caledonia River Middle Branch ) , before reaching its confluence with the Macalister River , near The Sisters , in the Shire of Wellington .
The Rum River is a slow , meandering channel that connects Minnesota 's Mille Lacs Lake with the Mississippi River .
The Ilisos is now routed straight to sea , coming to surface and running into the Saronic Gulf in the middle of Phaleron Bay .
The Eau Galle River is a tributary of the Chippewa River in western Wisconsin in the United States .
The Mopan River discharges to the Belize River as the Mopan merges with the Macal River ; the Belize River in turn terminates at the Caribbean Sea .
Supersonic speed is a rate of travel of an object that exceeds the speed of sound ( Mach 1 ) .

In algebraic geometry and commutative algebra , the Zariski topology is a topology on algebraic varieties , introduced primarily by Oscar Zariski and later generalized for making the set of prime ideals of a commutative ring a topological space , called the spectrum of the ring .

Agra schwarzeneggeri ( Erwin , 2002 ) is a species of carabid beetle named after `` the actor , Arnold Schwarzenegger , in reference to the markedly developed ( biceps - like ) middle femora of the males of this species reminiscent of the actor 's physique . ''
The Angora goat ( Turkish : Ankara keçisi ) is a breed of domestic goat that is named after Ankara , Turkey , historically known as Angora .
Ponticola rizensis is a species of gobiid fish endemic to Turkey where it is known only from the İyidere stream drainage , close to the cities of Rize ( from which the specific name is derived ) and Trabzon .
The Peter principle is a concept in management theory formulated by Laurence J. Peter in which the selection of a candidate for a position is based on the candidate 's performance in their current role , rather than on abilities relevant to the intended role .
The Bradford Hill criteria , otherwise known as Hill 's criteria for causation , are a group of minimal conditions necessary to provide adequate evidence of a causal relationship between an incidence and a possible consequence , established by the English epidemiologist Sir Austin Bradford Hill ( 1897 - -1991 ) in 1965 .
Roth 's spots are named after Moritz Roth .
U.S. Virgin Islands Highway 66 is a major east -- west arterial on St. Croix in the United States Virgin Islands and is named the Melvin H. Evans Highway in honor of the territory 's first elected governor .
The Schottky diode ( named after German physicist Walter H. Schottky ) , also known as hot carrier diode , is a semiconductor diode with a low forward voltage drop and a very fast switching action .
The Erich Fried Prize ( German : Erich - Fried - Preis ) is a literary prize in honour of the Austrian poet Erich Fried , and is awarded annually by the International Erich Fried Association for Literature and Language , based in Vienna .
The Tiebout model , also known as Tiebout sorting , Tiebout migration , or Tiebout hypothesis , is a positive political theory model first described by economist Charles Tiebout in his article `` A Pure Theory of Local Expenditures '' ( 1956 ) .
51823 Rickhusband ( 2001 OY28 ) is an asteroid named for astronaut Rick Husband , who was killed in the STS-107 ( Columbia ) space shuttle reentry disaster on February 1 , 2003 .

František Vymazal ( November 6 , 1841 -- April 6 , 1917 ) was a Czech polyglot and language textbooks writer .

Willis Burks II ( October 25 , 1935 -- November 21 , 2010 ) , sometimes credited as Willis Burks or Willis Burks , Jr. , was an American television , film , stage and voice actor whose acting career spanned more than thirty years .

Zacharias Papantoniou ( Greek : Ζαχαρίας Παπαντωνίου , Zacharias Papandoniou ) was a Greek writer .

Reynold B. Johnson ( July 16 , 1906 -- September 15 , 1998 ) was an American inventor and computer pioneer .
